          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The tariff week
</h2> 
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/trump-tariff-announcement.png" alt="Donald Trump holding a chart of reciprocal tariffs during a press conference." href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF"> 
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>President Donald Trump holds up a chart while speaking during a trade announcement event in the Rose Garden at the White House. Credits: Chip Somodevilla/Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
       
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">This was meant to be Trump’s big trade move. On the week starting April 2, chaos ensued when the US rolled out <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-12-04-2025-h1-1-sweeping-tariffs?source=website" target="_blank">sweeping tariffs:</a> a flat 10% on nearly all imports and a 145% rate on Chinese goods. Branded as “economic liberation,” the plan was pitched as a bold step to bring manufacturing back to the US.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">But the markets weren’t convinced. When the tariffs took effect on April 9, stocks sank, bond yields surged, and pressure mounted from business leaders, Republicans, and even Trump’s own advisers. Economists suggested that if the tariffs were implemented, the US would have increased its <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-12-04-2025-h1-2-recession-probability-up-to-45?source=website" target="_blank">recession probability up to 45%</a> in the next 12 months. </p>
        </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
